04723nam a22006975i 9780226654324DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018061748  a97802266543247 a10.7208/97802266543242doi  a(DE-B1597)535754  a(OCoLC)1138031822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aKF8972b.C48 2019 4aKF8972b.C53 2020 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a345.730752231 aChakravarti, Sonali, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRadical Enfranchisement in the Jury Room and Public Life /cSonali Chakravarti. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Mature Enough to Disobey: Jurors, Women, and Radical Enfranchisement in Tocqueville’s Democracy in America -- tTwo. Mistaken for Consensus: Hung Juries, the Allen Charge, and the End of Jury Deliberation -- tThree. No One but You: Jurors and the Internal Standard of Reasonable Doubt -- tFour. Guilty, Not Guilty, Nullify: Nullification in an Age of Abolition -- tFive. Radical Enfranchisement in the Jury Room -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJuries have been at the center of some of the most emotionally charged moments of political life. At the same time, their capacity for legitimate decision making has been under scrutiny, because of events like the acquittal of George Zimmerman by a Florida jury for the shooting of Trayvon Martin and the decisions of several grand juries not to indict police officers for the killing of unarmed black men. Meanwhile, the overall use of juries has also declined in recent years, with most cases settled or resolved by plea bargain. With Radical Enfranchisement in the Jury Room and Public Life, Sonali Chakravarti offers a full-throated defense of juries as a democratic institution. She argues that juries provide an important site for democratic action by citizens and that their use should be revived. The jury, Chakravarti argues, could be a forward-looking institution that nurtures the best democratic instincts of citizens, but this requires a change in civic education regarding the skills that should be cultivated in jurors before and through the process of a trial. Being a juror, perhaps counterintuitively, can guide citizens in how to be thoughtful rule-breakers by changing their relationship to their own perceptions and biases and by making options for collective action salient, but they must be better prepared and instructed along the way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aJury dutyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aJury nullificationzUnited States. 0aJuryzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  abias.  acivic participation.  ajury.  alaw.  aobedience.  aradical enfranchisement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020 Englishz978311070486008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020z9783110704587oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226654324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226654324.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070486-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles